quizzes.question:
Fill in the blanks to add the class names "text" and "menu" to the <p> element.
[!raw!]
{0}("p").addClass("{1}");

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Manipulating CSS [/h1]

jQuery has several methods for CSS manipulation.
The [b]addClass( )[/b] method adds one or more classes to the selected elements.
For example:
[b]HTML[/b]: [code format="html" ]<div>Some text</div>[/code]
[b]CSS[/b]: [code format="css" ].header {
  color: blue;
  font-size:x-large;
}[/code]
[b]JS[/b]: [code format="js" codeId="1115"]$("div").[b]addClass[/b]("header");[/code]
The above code assigns the div element the class "header".
[note]To specify multiple classes within the addClass() method, just separate them using spaces. For example, $("div").addClass("class1 class2 class3").[/note]

quizzes.question:
Which class name will the <p class="a b"></p> element have after the following code?
$("p").addClass("c");
$("p").removeClass("a c");

Will the paragraph have a border after this code?
<style> 
 .test{ border-style: solid; } 
</style> 
<p>Some text</p> 
<script> 
$(function() {
  $("p").addClass("test"); 
  $("p").toggleClass("test");
}); 
</script>

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]toggleClass()[/h1]

The [b]toggleClass()[/b] method toggles between adding/removing classes from the selected elements, meaning that if the specified class exists for the element, it is removed, and if it does not exist, it is added.
To demonstrate this in action, we will handle a button click event to toggle a class. We will learn more about events and their syntax in the coming modules.
[b]HTML[/b]: [code format="html" ]<p>Some text</p>
<button>Toggle Class</button>[/code]
[b]CSS[/b]: [code format="css" ].red { 
  color:red; 
  font-weight: bold;
}[/code]
[b]JS[/b]: [code format="js" codeId="1117"]$(function() {
  $("button").click(function() {
    $("p").[b]toggleClass[/b]("red");
  });
});[/code]
[note]The code above toggles the class name "red" upon clicking the button.[/note]
